  "output": "## N+1 query patterns\n\nNone — there's no database or API layer here. The only network call is the single Formspree POST in `ContactModal.tsx` on submit. Nothing to fix.\n\n## Unnecessary re-renders\n\n**`AboutSection.tsx` / `WorkSection.tsx` — translated arrays rebuilt every render**\n\n```ts\nconst services = serviceKeys.map((key) => ({\n  n: key, title: t(`about.services.${key}.title`), body: t(`about.services.${key}.body`),\n}))\n```\nThis runs on *every* render, including the 4 hover-state renders per item. Same pattern in `WorkSection.tsx` for `projects`. Fix:\n\n```ts\nconst services = useMemo(\n  () => serviceKeys.map((key) => ({\n    n: key, title: t(`about.services.${key}.title`), body: t(`about.services.${key}.body`),\n  })),\n  [t],\n)\n```\n\n**`AboutSection.tsx` — single `hovered` state re-renders the whole list**\n\n`setHovered(i)` on mouseEnter re-renders all 4 `<li>` items to recompute `isHovered` for each, just to toggle one. With only 4 items this is cheap, so low priority — but if you ever add more services, split into a memoized `ServiceItem` component keyed by `s.n`, or better, drop the JS state entirely and use CSS `:hover`/`group-hover` since the transition is pure visual state with no other side effects.\n\n**`Navbar.tsx` — unthrottled scroll handler doing DOM work**\n\n```ts\nwindow.addEventListener('scroll', update, { passive: true })\n```\n`update()` calls `document.elementFromPoint` + walks up the DOM computing styles on *every* scroll event — and Lenis re-emits scroll far more often than the browser paints. This is the real perf cost here (layout/style reads), not the `setState` calls (React already bails on identical primitives). Throttle to one call per frame:\n\n```ts\nlet ticking = false\nfunction onScroll() {\n  if (ticking) return\n  ticking = true\n  requestAnimationFrame(() => { update(); ticking = false })\n}\nwindow.addEventListener('scroll', onScroll, { passive: true })\n```\n\n## Caching opportunities\n\n**`ContactSection.tsx` — `vilniusOffset` recomputed every render**\n\n```ts\nconst vilniusOffset = new Intl.DateTimeFormat('en-US', { ... }).formatToParts(new Date())...\n```\nThis constructs a new `Intl.DateTimeFormat` and reformats on every render of a component that re-renders whenever `App`'s `contactOpen` toggles. The UTC offset only changes twice a year (DST). Memoize once per mount:\n\n```ts\nconst vilniusOffset = useMemo(() => (\n  new Intl.DateTimeFormat('en-US', { timeZone: 'Europe/Vilnius', timeZoneName: 'shortOffset' })\n    .formatToParts(new Date())\n    .find((p) => p.type === 'timeZoneName')?.value ?? 'GMT+2'\n), [])\n```\n\n**Same fix as above** for `services`/`projects` arrays — memoizing them also means downstream JSX (`.map`) doesn't rebuild props identity on every render, which matters if those items ever get wrapped in `React.memo`.\n\n## Memory leaks\n\nWent through every `useEffect` with a subscription/timer/rAF — cleanup is handled correctly everywhere I could fully see: `useLenis` destroys Lenis + removes the GSAP ticker fn + nulls the singleton; `CursorScroll` cancels its rAF and removes listeners; `Preloader` kills its timeline; `ContactModal`/`Navbar` clear timeouts/listeners on unmount.\n\nOne thing to verify (file was truncated): **`WorkSection.tsx`'s `watchHover` rAF loop**:\n```ts\nuseEffect(() => {\n  let raf: number\n  const tick = () => { ...; raf = requestAnimationFrame(tick) }\n  ...\n```\nMake sure the cleanup does `return () => cancelAnimationFrame(raf)` — same as `CursorScroll.tsx` does. If that return is missing in the untruncated part, it's a leak (the loop keeps running after unmount, holding refs to detached DOM nodes).\n\nNo other real leaks found — `lenisStore`'s module-level singleton is fine as long as only one `CinematicScrollLayer` ever mounts (true today).\n\n## Redundant computations\n\n- `services`/`projects` array construction (covered above — same fix, one `useMemo` closes both).\n- `vilniusOffset` (covered above).\n- Minor, skip: `Navbar`'s `spacerH ?? window.innerHeight * 4` fallback and `luminanceOf`'s regex — both cheap enough per call that memoizing would cost more than it saves.\n\n**Summary of concrete diffs worth making:** wrap the two translated-array constructions in `useMemo`, wrap `vilniusOffset` in `useMemo(() => ..., [])`, throttle `Navbar`'s scroll handler to `requestAnimationFrame`, and confirm `WorkSection`'s watch-hover rAF has a cancel-on-unmount. Everything else in this codebase is already following good patterns (rAF-driven visual loops instead of React state, `gsap.context`/`matchMedia` cleanup, memoized `TextReveal` chars).\n",
